1. Global Attributes Overview

Global Attributes are reusable attribute templates that you define once and link to any number of products. Instead of creating "Color" or "Size" separately on every product, you define them as Global Attributes with all their options, then simply link them to products that need them.

Step 1: Global Attributes List

The Global Attributes page shows all reusable attribute templates defined in your store. Each attribute has a type (Select, Color Swatch, Button Group, Image Swatch), an optional category, and shows how many options it has and how many products use it.

üí° Tips:
  • Click "+ New Global Attribute" to create a new template.
  • Attributes with zero product usage can be deleted directly from this page.
  • The "Used By" column shows how many products have linked this attribute.

2. Creating a Global Attribute

Creating a Global Attribute involves defining its basic properties. Once created, you can add metadata fields (structured extra data per option) and the actual option values.

Step 1: New Global Attribute Form

The creation form lets you define the attribute's internal name, display name, type, and category. The internal name should be lowercase and snake_case (e.g., "color", "material_type").

üí° Tips:
  • The internal name is used for lookups and cannot be changed after creation.
  • Display Name is what your shop administrators see in the UI.
  • Choose the type based on how the attribute should render in the storefront.

Step 2: Filled Creation Form

Here we're creating a "Color" attribute of type "Color Swatch" in the "Style" category. The description helps other administrators understand the purpose of this attribute.

Step 3: Attribute Created

After submission, you're redirected to the edit page where you can add metadata fields and options. The attribute is now saved and ready to be configured.

3. Metadata Fields (Rich Schema)

Metadata Fields let you attach structured extra data to each option. This is the "Rich Metadata Schema" concept ‚Äî instead of just "Red" as an option, you can also store the Pantone code, hex color, whether it's a premium color, a URL to a material sample photo, and more.

Step 1: Metadata Fields Section

Metadata fields define additional structured data that each option can carry. For example, a Color attribute might have a "Pantone Code" text field and a "Is Premium" boolean field. These fields appear as extra columns when adding options.

üí° Tips:
  • Field types: Text, Number, Boolean, Select, URL.
  • Required fields must be filled when adding new options.
  • Default values are pre-filled when creating new options.

Step 2: Adding a Metadata Field

Fill in the field name (snake_case), display name, type, and optionally a default value. Here we're adding a "Pantone Code" text field for our Color attribute.

Step 3: Metadata Field Added

The field appears in the table and will now show as an extra column in the Options section below. You can add multiple metadata fields to capture all the structured data you need.

Step 4: Multiple Metadata Fields

We've now added two metadata fields: "Pantone Code" (Text) and "Premium Color" (Boolean). These will appear as extra columns in both the options table and the add-option form.

4. Adding Options

Options are the actual values that customers can select. For a Color attribute, options might be "Black", "Tan", "Forest Green", etc. Each option can carry metadata defined by the metadata fields.

Step 1: Options Section

The Options section shows all available values for this attribute. Notice how the metadata fields we created appear as extra columns in both the table and the "Add" form.

Step 2: Adding an Option: Black

Fill in the value, display value, and color hex. The metadata fields (Pantone Code, Premium Color) appear as additional inputs in the form. Color hex is displayed as a swatch preview.

Step 3: Options Added

After adding several options, the table shows all values with their color swatches and metadata. Each option can be removed individually. The options are immediately available for linking to products.

üí° Tips:
  • Options are shared across all products that link this attribute.
  • When you link an attribute to a product, you can select which subset of options that product offers.
  • Color swatches are automatically rendered from the hex value.

5. Linking to a Product

Once you have global attributes defined with their options, you link them to individual products. This is where the reuse happens ‚Äî a single "Color" attribute with 20 options can be linked to 50 different products, and each product can select just the colors it offers.

Step 1: Product Global Attributes Tab

Navigate to the "Global Attributes" tab on any product to link global attribute templates. The "Link Global Attribute" form shows a dropdown of all available (unlinked) attributes.

üí° Tips:
  • A product can have multiple linked global attributes (e.g., Color + Size + Material).
  • Already-linked attributes don't appear in the dropdown.
  • Each link has a "role" that determines how it's used: Variant Axis, Filter Only, or Display Only.

Step 2: Linking a Global Attribute

Select "Color" from the dropdown and set the role to "Variant Axis". Variant Axis means this attribute will generate purchasable product variants. "Filter Only" is used for storefront filtering without creating variants. "Display Only" shows information but doesn't affect filtering or variants.

Step 3: Attribute Linked ‚Äî Option Selection

After linking, a card appears showing all options from the global attribute template. Use the checkboxes to select which options this specific product offers. Not every product needs every color ‚Äî you can cherry-pick.

üí° Tips:
  • Use "Select All" checkbox in the header to quickly select all options.
  • Price Modifier lets you add/subtract from the base price for specific options.
  • Click "Save Selections" after checking the options you want.
  • Click "Unlink" to remove the attribute from this product entirely.

Step 4: Configuring Selections & Price Modifiers

Select the options this product offers and optionally set price modifiers. A price modifier adds to (or subtracts from) the product's base price for that option.

Step 5: Selections Saved

The card updates to show the selection count (e.g., "2/3 selected"). The HTMX-powered UI updates the card in-place without a full page reload.

6. Attribute Types Reference

ForgeCommerce supports four attribute types, each with a different visual presentation in the storefront. Choose the type that best fits the kind of data the attribute represents.

Step 1: Button Group Type ‚Äî Size Attribute

A "Button Group" attribute renders options as clickable buttons in the storefront (S, M, L, XL). This is ideal for sizes, quantities, or any discrete set of options that don't need color swatches.

Step 2: Multiple Attributes on List Page

The list page now shows both our Color (Color Swatch) and Size (Button Group) attributes. You can create as many global attributes as your store needs.

üí° Tips:
  • Select: Standard dropdown selector.
  • Color Swatch: Visual color circle/square pickers.
  • Button Group: Horizontal button-style selectors.
  • Image Swatch: Thumbnail image pickers (e.g., fabric patterns).
